description: Mandatory KDoc rules (language, links, scope)
globs: **/*.kt
alwaysApply: false
---

# Documentation (KDoc / comments) — mandatory

## Language
- **English only** for KDoc/README/public API comments. Never write documentation in other languages.

## KDoc links
- **Forbidden:** fully qualified names in link targets (no `[Foo][full.package.Foo]`).
- **Required:** use only simple names that resolve via imports: `[Foo]`, `[SomeType.member]`.
- Every referenced type/member in KDoc links must be importable and imported in the same file.
- If a target is in another module and cannot be imported, use **plain text** (no link).
- **Forbidden — deferred prose:** do not substitute a full explanation with a pointer to another declaration’s KDoc (e.g. “same as [OtherRoutes.FOO]”, “see [OtherRoutes]”). For HTTP route constants, repeat the full contract text per `docs-kdoc-type-requirements.mdc` (HTTP route constants).

## Scope rules
- In `object` / class-level KDoc, do **not** link to function parameters by name (out of scope). Use plain text and move parameter links to function-level KDoc.
- When documentation is requested for a **package**, the scope includes all subpackages.
- For package documentation requests, **do not** add new Kotlin files that exist only to carry a package-level KDoc comment (no types, no functions, no other declarations). Document existing declarations in that package tree instead.

## Documentation tasks — definition of done
- When the user asks to document a **package**, **directory**, **set of files**, or **module** without narrowing scope, **public API** in that scope must satisfy the **Public API** rules in `docs-kdoc-type-requirements.mdc` in full.
- In particular, for **`interface` types** that means **both** class-level KDoc **and** KDoc on **every public** `fun` / `val` member that is part of the contract (typically: purpose, `@param` for each parameter, `@return` for non-`Unit` results; for `Unit`, still state the outcome in the summary or a brief `@return` when it clarifies error handling).
- **Do not** treat such a request as complete if interfaces only have class-level KDoc while methods are undocumented, **unless** the user explicitly limits scope (e.g. “class-level only”, or names specific declarations).
- When the user names a **single** type, document that type completely per the same type rules (class + all members that require KDoc).

## Comments
- Use inline comments sparingly; do not narrate obvious behavior.
- Prefer clear naming and KDoc for public surface; comment only when intent/constraints are non-obvious.
